      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Mesh convergence study — Richardson extrapolation on shear stress QoI",
      "description": "Three-level mesh refinement study using Richardson extrapolation. Grid convergence index (GCI) for volume-averaged shear stress < 2.1% on fine mesh (12.4 M cells). Discretization error deemed acceptable for MRL 2.",
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-gcbp-cfd-mesh-convergence-dataset"
    }
  ],
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/cpb-hemolysis-model-adequate",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "CFD model is adequate for identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions in the FDA GCBP under CPB conditions",
      "description": "The CFD hemolysis model, employing the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law damage accumulation formulation with SST k-omega turbulence closure, has been assessed against the full body of FDA interlaboratory bench-top hemolysis data and internal mesh-convergence studies. Across all five evaluated flow-speed combinations the model reproduces experimental normalized index of hemolysis values within the stated experimental uncertainty, and the relative hemolysis index (RH) predictions satisfy the RH < 1 acceptance criterion for Class II CPB devices. The assessment team concludes that the model is fit for the intended regulatory purpose of identifying worst-case operating conditions and supporting a 510(k) substantial-equivalence argument for the predicate device comparison. This conclusion is grounded in the validation activities documented in Morrison et al. (2019), the FDA GCBP interlaboratory study (Hariharan et al., 2011), and internal discretization-error analyses, all of which collectively demonstrate that numerical and physical modelling uncertainties are bounded at levels acceptable for Model Risk Level 2."
    }
  ],
